<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by Department for Education</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:right; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">SCP0</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">0</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">07</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:right; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">Department for Education</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:center; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">School places</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.47pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The school age population is growing rapidly – the Government wants to work with local authorities, schools and potential new school sponsors to make sure that there are enough good school places. We want parents to be able to feel confident that their children will get places at a good school in their area. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Government’s approach is to: </span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52.87pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">more than double the funding given to local authorities to create new school places;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52.87pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">recognise that local authorities are best placed to fulfil their existing statutory duty to ensure every child has a place;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52.26pt; orphans:0; padding-left:4.44pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">recognise</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that free schools are also providing additional places where there is parental demand and are disproportionately located in areas of basic need.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 3.3pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The school age population is growing rapidly, and especially in London</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 3.3pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.47pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The number of births increased by more than a fifth between 2002 and 2011, meaning that 120,000 more children are now born every year. This is the largest ten-year increase since the post-war baby boom, caused both by higher birth rates and higher immigration over the last two decades. ONS estimates reported the rise in birth rates from 2004, and predicted that this would feed through into a significant increase in demand for primary places from 2010, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">yet funding for additional school places did not increase significantly until the 2010 Spending Round.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Office for National Statistics figures show that by 2020 there will be around 21% more primary age children than in 2010.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.47pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Government collects data every year about the number of school places available in every local authority area (and local planning areas) and about local authorities’ forecasts of the number of pupils who will need places in the medium term (5-7 years)</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Before 2010, the data collected by the Department was patchy and insufficiently granular. This Government improved the range and quality of data gathered so that we are now much clearer about where need is greatest. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">These data show not only the overall scale of the challenge, but also the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">areas where the growth is most concentrated. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Overall, the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">greatest </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">need</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for new school places is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in London and the South East. The data also show that there are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">other concentrations, and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">local ‘hotspots’ – for example where the school-age population is rising in a town, but not in the surrounding country-side. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Providing funding to l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ocal authorities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">to ensure </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">there are enough places</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.47pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Local authorities have a statutory duty to ensure that there are enough school places available.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Central government provides local authorities with ‘basic need’ funding to help them meet this duty.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.47pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Decisions taken by this Government mean that between the financial years 2011-12 and 2014-15 central </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">government</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is providing £5 billion in basic need funding. This is more than double the £1.9 billion allocated over the preceding four-year period (2007-08 to 2010-11), even though the population increase had meant that significant </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">numbers of new places were needed during this period. The proportion of the Department’s capital budget dedicated to creating new places in areas of basic need has increased from 7.5% in the previous spending review period to 28.3% in the current spending review period. These funds created</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> an estimated 190,000 additional places between 2010 and September 2013</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.47pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">New places can either be created by expanding existing schools or by opening new schools. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Where a new school is needed, local authorities have the powers to invite </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">academy proposers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to open a new </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">school</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is important to create not just new school places, but also high quality new school places. L</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ocal authorities have worked closely with academies to support their expansion</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, and academies themselves seek out such opportunities</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We want authorities to encourage and support good and outstanding schools of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">all</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> types to expand, to create the high quality places that parents want</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.47pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The £5 billion allocated to creating new places does not include spending on free schools. Increasing basic need funding is the Government’s principal response to the shortage of places, but free schools also help. They are disproportionately opening in areas with a shortage of places – 7 in 10 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">open mainstream free schools are in areas of basic need</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Free schools can be set up in areas where there are surplus places, because they satisfy parental demand for high quality school places that the LA has not prioritised or delivered. All </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">open and planned free schools will deliver 130,000</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> additional</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> places</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> once full.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Allocating funding to where it is needed</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.47pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We work </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">with local authorities to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">fine-tune</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e way that we allocate funding. W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e look at the capacity and need for new places in each year group and within each local authority ‘planning area’ to make sure that we recognise that new places need to be within reasonable travelling distance for parents</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> wherever possible, and allocate funding accordingly</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.47pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">money spent on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> creating a new school place </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">varies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> significantly, depending on a wide range of factors</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, including that some LAs achieve better value for money than others</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We estimate that t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he total basic need allocations over the course of the Parliament </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> enough to fund the cost of the new school p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">laces needed during this period.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">F</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">inal cost</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> will also depend on local authorities’ decisions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and actions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. We have started to collect data about these costs </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">– and which authorities are most efficient – and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">will look closely at the evidence it provides. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">On 1 March 2013, we announced allocations for two years (2013-14 and 2014-15), in order to help local authorities to plan ahead. We secured a good, long term capital settlement for the next spending period, and will be able to allocate £7.5 billion to fund the estimated 500,000 additional places needed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We will continue to seek to make allocations which give LAs the best opportunities to plan ahead.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 3.3pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 3.3pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">October 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> SCAP 2012, published 1 March 2013. The data includes the number of school places available at the end of the academic year 2011-12 and forecasts of the number of children who will need school places in September 2015, and so it is not surprising that there is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">a difference in these figures, as local authorities create</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> new places each year. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> The Targeted Basic Need programme invited LAs to apply for funding to expand existing schools or establish new schools – academies make up 22% of the expansion projects. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> The Academies Capital Maintenance Fund has supported 60 popular and successful academies to expand, and 25% of bids to this fund are to support expansion. </span></p></body></html>